# nl-rag distilled facts — domain: buzkashi
# one declarative sentence per line; load with:  neuron --db app.db import pack.facts --scope knowledge
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] The first set of rules was published in 1937 by the Amateur Softball Association, in the same manual as the rules for fastpitch softball.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] Game play for 16-inch softball is mostly consistent with standard softball game play.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] In contrast to standard, or 12-inch (30.48 cm) softball, it is played with a ball 16 inches (40.64 cm) in circumference.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] It is common to see higher arched pitching, and balls/strikes are determined by where the ball lands and crosses the batter's body.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] Leagues may form co-ed, all-male, or all-female teams.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] Additionally, teams may choose competitive or recreational leagues.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] There may be rule variations associated with the specific field or league of play.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] When playing in a co-ed league, there may be other rules that relate to the male-to-female ratio of team members and batting order.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] The National Softball Association (NSA) also has a published set of rules governing 16-inch softball play.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] The earliest known softball game of any kind was played at the Farragut Boat Club in Chicago on Thanksgiving Day 1887.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] The first softball was a wrapped up boxing glove and the bat was a broom.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] Play was encouraged by a reporter, George Hancock, who had been looking on.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] Harvard and Yale students played the game while waiting to hear the results of the annual Harvard-Yale football game.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] Until the turn of the 20th century, ball sizes ranged from 12 to 17 inches in circumference.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] The 16-inch softball was eventually adopted in Chicago, perhaps because it did not travel as far as the popular 12- or 14-inch balls.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] This also may have allowed for play on smaller playgrounds or even indoors, accommodating the Chicago landscape and climate.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] Another possible advantage of the 16-inch ball was that it allowed everyone to play barehanded, and gloves were a rare luxury as the Great Depression hit Chicago particularly hard.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] After the first national championship held in 1933 at the Century of Progress World's Fair, the sport grew in popularity.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] A professional league was formed that lasted through the 1950s.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] Teams drew crowds of over 10,000 each night.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] Leagues continue today but not at the same level of popularity.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] There are co-ed recreational leagues, competitive leagues and even a league for Chicago Public School students.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] Many local organizations host regular season play, typically weekly games, as well as their own playoff systems.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] National organizations, such as the NSA, host a variety of tournaments.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] By placing well in NSA tournaments, teams can qualify and compete for the 16-inch softball world series.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] Because local leagues may have slight variations in rules, the NSA world series is played by its own set of world series rules.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] One notable change is that Chicago area players, who typically are not allowed to wear gloves, may choose to wear gloves in world series games.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] Games are played with a deBeer Clincher 16" ball and gloves are used.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] In 1996 Al Maag and Tony Reibel established the 16" Softball Hall of Fame.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] Since inception, the organization has held annual inductee dinners attended by over 600 guests.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] There is a museum in Forest Park, Illinois, a suburb of Chicago.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] 16inchsoftballhof.com The Chicago 16" Softball Hall of Fame is a registered 501(c) not-for-profit organization.
[src:buzkashi/16-inch-softball] The game can be seen being played in multiple scenes in the 1986 film *About Last Night*, whose storyline was set in Chicago.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] 3x3 has been a basketball format long played in streets and gyms across the world, albeit in a less formal way.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] Starting in the late 2000s, 3x3 game rules started to become standardized throughout the United States, most notably through the Gus Macker and Hoop It Up tournament series, which held large events across the country that included teams and players from all skill levels.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] In 1992, Adidas launched its now-discontinued streetball competition.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] Since then, the number of 3x3 events and competitions has been steadily growing around the world.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] A Romanian organization, Sport Arena Streetball, began hosting 3x3 events in Bucharest as early as 2005, helping to grow the sport locally and regionally before formal FIBA rules were introduced.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] FIBA first test 3x3 at the 2007 Asian Indoor Games in Macau, followed by further test events in April 2008 in the Dominican Republic and October 2008 in Indonesia.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] The international debut of 3x3 under FIBA rules occurred at the 2009 Asian Youth Games, where 19 teams competed in the boys' tournament and 16 teams competed in the girls' tournament, with all games held at Anglican High School in Tanah Merah, Singapore.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] 3x3 made its worldwide competitive debut at the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics in Singapore, where 20 teams competed in both boys' and girls' categories, with games held at the Youth Space.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] Since then, FIBA has regularly held world championships in both open and U18 categories.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] Bucharest, later called the "Mecca of 3x3 basketball" by Sports Illustrated, hosted the first FIBA Europe 3x3 Championships in 2014, an event that helped establish organized 3x3 competition across Europe.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] In subsequent years, the city also hosted international 3x3 tournaments, attracting teams from outside Europe.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] FIBA developed 3x3 as a standalone discipline with its own format and regular international competitions.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball made its Olympic debut at the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] The 3x3 basketball variation has also been used in several tournaments, such as the Nike 3ON3 Tournament and Spokane Hoopfest, the largest 3x3 basketball tournament in the world, held annually in Spokane, Washington.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] FIBA releases from time-to-time a supplement to its official basketball rules specifically for 3x3.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] The rules state that regular FIBA rules apply to all situations not specifically addressed in the FIBA 3x3 rules.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] The current set, both in an abbreviated version and longer format, was published in August 2019.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] The current rules depart from regular full-court basketball in the following ways.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] Each team consists of three players and one substitute.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] Each team must have three players on the court when the game begins.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] The game is played on a half-court with one basket.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] The American NBA & WNBA standard half-court distance is 15.24 m (50 ft) wide & 14.33 m (47 ft) long.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] The ball is the size of a size 6 basketball (720 mm, 28.5 in) as used in the women's full-court game and its mass is that of the size 7 standard (620 g, 22 oz) used in the men's full-court game.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] A coin toss is held immediately before the game, and the winning team of the coin flip can choose to take possession of the ball at the start of the game, or take the first possession of a potential overtime period.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] In turn, this means that if the game goes into overtime, the first possession goes to the team that started the game on defense.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] The game begins with the defensive team passing the ball to the offensive team to signify the start of the game.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] All offensive players must begin outside of the arc (the opposite side of the arc of the net), and the defensive team must begin inside of the arc.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] Once the offensive team receives the ball, the clock starts.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] This exchange is also used to restart the game from any dead ball situation.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] The game is a single period of a maximum 10 minutes and the winner is the first team to score 21 or the team with the higher score at the end of the 10 minutes; scoring 21 points immediately ends the game.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] Every successful shot inside the arc, including free throws, is awarded one point, while every successful shot outside of the arc ("downtown") is awarded two points.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] After a made goal or free throw (except for technical or unsportsmanlike fouls and team fouls 10 or more; see below), play restarts with a player from the non-scoring team taking the ball directly under the basket and then dribbling or passing it to a point behind the arc.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] The defense is not allowed to play for the ball inside the block/charge semi-circle under the basket.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] In any held-ball situation, the defensive team is granted possession.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] The offensive team must attempt a shot for a goal within 12 seconds.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] An offensive player may also not dribble inside the arc with their back or side to the basket for more than 3 consecutive seconds.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] For either violation the defensive team is granted possession.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] There is a Trent Tucker Rule in which with up to 0.2 seconds left in regulation or on the shot clock, a high lob, or tip-in must be made.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] A tie in regulation time leads to an untimed overtime period, after a one-minute intermission.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] Whichever team began the game as the defensive team, begins overtime as the offensive team.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] The first team to score two points wins the game.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] Note: if a game is tied at 20 at the end of regulation, a team scoring their 21st point in overtime does not end the game.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] Substitutions can occur only in a dead-ball situation; a substitute can only enter from behind the end line opposite the basket, and the substitution becomes official once the player leaving the game has "tagged up" by making physical contact with the substitute.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] Each team is allowed one 30 second time-out per game.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] Each personal or technical foul counts as one team foul, while each unsportsmanlike or disqualifying foul counts as two team fouls.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] Personal fouls during the act of shooting inside the arc are awarded one free throw, while fouls during the act of shooting behind the arc and the shot is unsuccessful are awarded two free throws.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] Team fouls 7, 8 and 9 are awarded two free throws, and all team fouls thereafter are awarded two free throws and possession of the ball.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] The "bonus" rule specifically supersedes the normal rule for fouls in the act of shooting.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] The un-timed overtime period is considered extension of regulation for purpose of team fouls.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] The first unsportsmanlike foul against a player results in two free throws.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] A second unsportsmanlike foul, or a disqualifying foul, results in two free throws and possession.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] A player who commits two unsportsmanlike fouls is disqualified.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] A team loses the game by default if all of its players are disqualified.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] All technical fouls result in one free throw, with possession going to the team that was entitled to possession at that time.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] If a foul is committed that results in the non-fouling team retaining possession, i.e. a technical or "unsportsmanlike" foul, the non-fouling team will receive the exchange outside of the arc.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] Offensive fouls, if not technical, unsportsmanlike, or disqualifying, never result in free throws, regardless of the number of team fouls.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] In the case of a double foul, no free throws are awarded to either team, regardless of team foul count or whether the double fouls were unsportsmanlike.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] FIBA sees 3x3 as a major vehicle for promotion of the game of basketball throughout the world.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] FIBA Secretary General and IOC member Patrick Baumann explained: "The 3x3 concept has all the elements and skills required for basketball, it has inspired and will continue to inspire many great players in the future.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] At the same time, it is the easiest and one of the most-effective ways to bring youngsters to basketball, keep them and promote our game.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] FIBA is pursuing a strategy to implement 3x3.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] FIBA has developed a digital community that acts as a repository for all FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events worldwide and offers all players an individual world ranking based on the points earned by players at FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] Any event around the world can become FIBA-endorsed by using FIBA's freeware, EventMaker, to organise the event.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] All FIBA-endorsed 3x3 events are classified within an established competition hierarchy, thus forming an official competition network.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] The pinnacle of this competition network is the FIBA 3x3 World Tour, which includes a series of World Tour Masters and one Final.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] A team can qualify for a World Tour Masters by playing in any of the designated World Tour qualifiers.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] The North American National Basketball Association (NBA) has also embraced 3x3.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] Since 2016, the NBA has held a summer series of tournaments known as "Dew NBA 3X", where local amateur players from around the US compete in regional events for cash prizes and a finals berth.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] The men's and women's NBA 3X champions then advance to the USA Basketball national 3x3 championship to potentially represent their country internationally.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] These tournaments also include live music performances, 3-point shooting contests for fans, an *NBA 2K* eSports competition, and appearances from current NBA players.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] The qualification system for the FIBA 3x3 World Cups for men and women differs radically from the system used for FIBA full-court competitions.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] According to *The New York Times*, 3x3 has "an unusual qualifying system designed to grow the sport all year long as much as find the best teams for the World Cup." National team entries are based strictly on a country's official 3x3 ranking.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] The ranking system for national teams also considers individual player rankings.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] For example, the US women's team qualified for the 2018 World Cup while the men's team did not, even though the men were ranked higher than the women on the cutoff date.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] Participating in a FIBA-sanctioned 3x3 event can earn ranking points; according to a FIBA executive, "Andorra has heavy participation every weekend." The current concentration of ranking events in Europe makes it more difficult for non-European nations, especially the US, to qualify.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] The aforementioned FIBA executive, when asked about the prospect of the 2020 Olympic debut of 3x3 potentially lacking any participation from the US, admitted that "a lot of teams want to beat the US.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] After the 2010 Summer Youth Olympics, FIBA established a regular World Cup that always includes men and women competing simultaneously in open, U23 and U18 categories.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] World Cups are played every year, except in years when there are Youth Olympic Games or Olympic Games.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] The COVID-19 pandemic caused the cancellation of the 2020 event.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] Classification to the World Cup is based on the 3x3 Federation Ranking, which ranks all National Federations based on the 3x3 Individual World Ranking points of their top 100 nationals in the respective category (i.e. men, women, U23 men, U23 women, U18 men, and U18 women).
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball became a regular European Games contest since its introduction at the 2015 European Games in Baku, Azerbaijan.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball made a debut in Olympic programme for the 2020 Summer Olympics in Tokyo, Japan, for both men and women.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] 3x3 basketball was included in 2022 Commonwealth Games in Birmingham, England.
[src:buzkashi/3x3-basketball] After the 2022 Russian invasion of Ukraine, FIBA banned Russian teams and officials from participating in FIBA 3x3 Basketball competitions.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] The **85th Academy Awards** ceremony, presented by the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences (AMPAS), honored the best films of 2012 and took place on February 24, 2013, at the Dolby Theatre in Hollywood, Los Angeles, beginning at 5:30 p.m.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] The ceremony was the first in the Academy's 85-year history to adopt the phrase "The Oscars" as the ceremony's official name during the broadcast and marketing.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] During the ceremony, the Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences presented Academy Awards (commonly referred to as Oscars) in 24 categories.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] The ceremony was televised in the United States by ABC, and produced by Craig Zadan and Neil Meron and directed by Don Mischer.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] Actor Seth MacFarlane hosted the show for the first time.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] In related events, the Academy held its 4th annual Governors Awards ceremony at the Grand Ballroom of the Hollywood and Highland Center on December 1, 2012.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] On February 9, 2013, in a ceremony at The Beverly Hills Hotel in Beverly Hills, California, the Academy Awards for Technical Achievement were presented by hosts Chris Pine and Zoe Saldaña.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] The nominees for the 85th Academy Awards were announced on January 10, 2013, at 5:38 a.m.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] PST (13:38 UTC) at the Samuel Goldwyn Theater in Beverly Hills, California, by Seth MacFarlane, host of the ceremony, and actress Emma Stone.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] *Lincoln* received the most nominations with twelve total, and *Life of Pi* came in second with eleven.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] The winners were announced during the awards ceremony on February 24, 2013.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] *Argo* was the fourth film to win Best Picture without a directing nomination, following 1927's *Wings*, 1932's *Grand Hotel*, and 1989's *Driving Miss Daisy*.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] As co-producer of *Argo*, George Clooney became the third individual to win Oscars for both acting and producing.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] By virtue of his nomination for Best Original Song in *Ted*, host MacFarlane became the sixth person since James Franco, who was a co-host and a Best Actor nominee during the 83rd ceremony in 2011, to host the ceremony while receiving a nomination in the same year.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] *Silver Linings Playbook* was the fourteenth film to earn nominations in all four acting categories, and the first since *Reds* in 1981.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] At age 22, Best Actress winner Jennifer Lawrence became the second-youngest winner in that category.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] With his third win for Best Lead Actor, Daniel Day-Lewis became the first three-time winner in that category.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] He also was the sixth performer to win at least three acting Oscars.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] *Amour* was the fourth film nominated simultaneously for Best Picture and Best Foreign Language Film in the same year.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] At age nine, Quvenzhané Wallis became the youngest nominee for Best Actress and the youngest female acting nominee overall.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] Meanwhile, Emmanuelle Riva (aged 85) was the oldest nominee for Best Actress.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] This marked the first time in Oscar history that all five nominees in an acting category (Best Supporting Actor) were all previous winners.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] *Skyfall* and *Zero Dark Thirty*'s joint win in the Best Sound Editing category was the sixth occurrence of a tie in Oscar history.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] *Skyfall* won the award for Best Original Song, becoming the first Bond song to win the award.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] Winners are listed first, highlighted in **boldface**, and indicated with a double dagger (‡).
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] The following individuals, listed in order of appearance, presented awards or performed musical numbers.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] Due to declining interest and viewership in recent ceremonies, the Academy hired a new production team in an attempt to improve ratings and revive interest in the ceremony.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] Reports surfaced that Academy then-president Tom Sherak approached television producer Lorne Michaels for producing duties with actor and comedian Jimmy Fallon as host.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] However, the telecast's broadcaster ABC objected to these selections, and both men declined afterward.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] With newly elected Academy president Hawk Koch assuming leadership duties, the Academy hired Neil Meron and Craig Zadan in August 2012 to produce the ceremony.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] Two months later, the Academy announced that actor, director, animator, singer, and comedian Seth MacFarlane would host the telecast.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] MacFarlane expressed that it was truly an honor and a thrill to be asked to host Academy Awards commenting, "It's truly an overwhelming privilege to be asked to host the Oscars.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] As evident by the numerous musical numbers featured throughout the telecast, the ceremony was billed as a salute to music and the movies.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] In keeping with the theme of the evening, numerous film scores from various motion pictures were played intermittently throughout the ceremony; most notable was John Williams' theme music from *Jaws*, which was used to goad winners off the stage if their acceptance speeches were overly long.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] In a departure from having the orchestra perform in the same theatre, composer Williams Ross conducted the orchestra from a studio inside the Capitol Records Building a mile away.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] Several other people were involved with the telecast and its promotion.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] Tony Award-winning art director Derek McLane designed a new set and stage design for the ceremony.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] Rob Ashford served as choreographer for several musical numbers during the event.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] Comedians Ben Gleib and Annie Greenup served as correspondents and hosts of "Oscar Road Trip", a nationwide bus tour promoting the ceremony in eleven major cities across the United States.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] Six young film students from colleges across the country, who were selected from a contest conducted by AMPAS and MtvU, were recruited to appear onstage to deliver Oscar statuettes to the presenters during the gala.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] In January 2012, AMPAS announced that it would create electronic voting system starting with the 2013 ceremony as another method for members to select the nominees and winners during the process.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] According to AMPAS Chief Operating Officer Ric Robertson, the implementation of the digital ballot was designed to increase participation among members in the voting process and to provide an alternative method of voting in case of emergency.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] Despite several Academy officials denying such reasons, some industry insiders speculated that the introduction of electronic voting was another move toward moving future awards galas to January.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] The deadline to submit nomination ballots was originally scheduled for January 3, but technological errors and glitches prompted the Academy to move the deadline one day later.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] None of the nine Best Picture nominees were among the top ten releases in box office during the nominations.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] However, four of those films had already earned $100 million in American and Canadian ticket sales.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] At the time of the announcement of nominations on January 10, *Lincoln* was the highest-grossing film among the Best Picture nominees with $144 million in domestic box office receipts.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] The other three films to earn $100 million prior to nominations were *Django Unchained* with $112 million, *Argo* with $110 million, and *Les Misérables* with $103 million.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] Of the top 50 grossing movies of the year, 61 nominations went to 15 films on the list.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] Only *Brave* (8th), *Wreck-It Ralph* (13th), *Lincoln* (17th), *Django Unchained* (23rd), *Argo* (26th), *Les Misérables* (27th), *Flight* (30th), and *Life of Pi* (31st) were nominated for Best Picture, Best Animated Feature, or any of the directing, acting, or screenwriting awards.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] The other top 50 box office hits that earned nominations were *Marvel's The Avengers* (1st), *Skyfall* (4th), *The Hobbit: An Unexpected Journey* (6th), *Ted* (13th), *Snow White and the Huntsman* (15th), *Prometheus* (20th), and *Mirror Mirror* (44th).
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] During the opening monologue, MacFarlane is told by James T.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] Kirk (William Shatner) (Captain Kirk set in the next day) about how he was going to ruin the telecast, Captain Kirk then shows him a music video where MacFarlane sings *We Saw Your Boobs*.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] Its lyrics lists out movies that featured scenes of actresses' disrobing.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] On the positive side, *The Guardian* reported, "MacFarlane was employed partly to puncture the event's pomposity, which he did by lightheartedly pointing out that some of the world's most self-important people regularly get their kit off for money".
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] SheKnows wondered if the live reaction of some of the actresses were indeed acting as the "pre-recorded spoof apparently looked real enough for social media to worry about it".
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] On the negative side, actress Jane Fonda stated, "if they want to stoop to that, why not list all the penises we've seen?
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] From topical jabs about domestic violence to singing about 'boobs' during a film's rape scene, Seth MacFarlane crossed the line from humor to misogyny." Amy Davidson of *The New Yorker* interpreted the song as hostile to women.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] In a press release statement, the Academy defended MacFarlane for expressing his artistic freedom, "If the Oscars are about anything, they're about creative freedom.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] The show received a mixed reception from media publications.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] Some media outlets were more critical of the show.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] Other media outlets received the broadcast and more positively.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] *Chicago Tribune* television critic Nina Metz lauded MacFarlane for keeping "a solid handle on the proceedings." She also remarked that the host "opened with a series of jokes that were bona fide winners, landing on just the right tone: confident but not cocksure".
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] The American telecast on ABC drew in an average of 40.38 million people over its length, which was a 3% increase from the previous year's ceremony.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] An estimated 77.92 million total viewers watched all or part of the awards.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] The show also drew higher Nielsen ratings compared to the two previous ceremonies with 24.47% of households watching over a 35.65 share.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] In addition, the program scored its highest key demo ratings in six years with a 13.71 rating over a 33.45 share among viewers in the 18–49 demographic.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] In July 2013, the ceremony presentation received nine nominations for the 65th Primetime Emmys.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] The following month, the ceremony didn't win any of the nominations.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] The annual *In Memoriam* segment was presented by actor/producer/director George Clooney.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] The montage featured an excerpt of the main title from *Out of Africa* by composer John Barry.
[src:buzkashi/85th-academy-awards] At the end of the tribute, singer Barbra Streisand sang "The Way We Were" from the film of the same name in tribute to composer Marvin Hamlisch.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] An ethnic Uzbek from a peasant family in Jawzjan province, Dostum joined the People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan (PDPA) as a teenager before enlisting in the Afghan Army and training as a paratrooper, serving in his native region around Sheberghan.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Following the outbreak of the Soviet–Afghan War, Dostum commanded a KHAD paramilitary unit and eventually gained a reputation for defeating mujahideen commanders in northern Afghanistan and even persuading some to defect to the communist cause.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] As a result, the communist government gained effective control over the country's north.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] He achieved several promotions in the army and was honored as a "Hero of Afghanistan" by President Mohammed Najibullah in 1988.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] By this time he was commanding up to 45,000 troops in the region under his responsibility.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Following the dissolution of the Soviet Union, Dostum played a central role in the collapse of Najibullah's government by "defecting" to the mujahideen; the division-sized loyal forces he commanded in the north became an independent paramilitary of his newly founded party called Junbish-e Milli.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] He allied with Ahmad Shah Massoud and together they captured Kabul, before another civil war loomed.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Initially supporting the new government of Burhanuddin Rabbani, he switched sides in 1994 by allying with Gulbuddin Hekmatyar, but he backed Rabbani again by 1996.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] During this time he remained in control of the country's north which functioned as a relatively stable proto-state, but remained a loose partner of Massoud in the Northern Alliance.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] A year later, Mazar-i-Sharif was overrun by his former aide Abdul Malik Pahlawan, resulting in a battle in which he regained control.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] In 1998, the city was overrun by the Taliban and Dostum fled the country until returning to Afghanistan in 2001, joining the Northern Alliance forces after the US invasion and leading his loyal faction in the Fall of Mazar-i-Sharif.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] After the fall of the Taliban-led government, he joined interim president Hamid Karzai's administration as Deputy Defense Minister and later served as chairman Joint Chiefs of Staff of the Afghan Army, a role often viewed as ceremonial.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] His militia feuded with forces loyal to general Atta Muhammad Nur.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Dostum was a candidate in the 2004 elections, and was an ally of victorious Karzai in the 2009 elections.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] From 2011, he was part of the leadership council of the National Front of Afghanistan along with Ahmad Zia Massoud and Mohammad Mohaqiq.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] He served as Vice President of Afghanistan in Ashraf Ghani's administration from 2014 to 2020.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] In 2020, he was promoted to the rank of marshal after a political agreement between Ghani and former Chief Executive Abdullah Abdullah.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] On 11 August 2021 during the Taliban's nationwide offensive, Dostum fled across Hairatan to Uzbekistan.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] In 2021 he pledged allegiance to the National Resistance Front of Afghanistan, and formed the *Supreme Council of National Resistance of the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan* in opposition to the new Taliban government.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Dostum now resides in exile in Turkey, and on 15 September 2024 urged groups opposed to Taliban rule to form a government-in-exile.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Dostum is a controversial figure in Afghanistan.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] He is seen as a capable and fierce military leader and remains wildly popular among the Uzbek community in the country.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Many of his supporters call him "Pasha" (پاشا), an honorable Uzbek/Turkic term.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] However, he has also been widely accused of committing atrocities and war crimes, most notoriously the suffocation of up to 1,000 Taliban fighters in the Dasht-i-Leili massacre, and he was widely feared among the populace.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] In 2018, the International Criminal Court (ICC) was reported to be considering launching an inquiry into whether Dostum had engaged in war crimes in Afghanistan.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Dostum was born in 1954 in Khwaja Du Koh near Sheberghan in Jowzjan province, Afghanistan.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Coming from an impoverished ethnic Uzbek family, he received a very basic traditional education as he was forced to drop out of school at a young age.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] From there, he took up work in the village's major gas fields.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Dostum began working in 1970 in a state-owned gas refinery in Sheberghan.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] He began participating in union politics when the republican government led by Daoud Khan started to arm the staff of the workers in the oil and gas refineries.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] The reason for this was to create "groups for the Defense of the Revolution".
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] As a result of the new communist ideas entering Afghanistan in the 1970s, Dostum enlisted in the Afghan Army in 1976.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] He received his basic military training in Jalalabad and his squadron was deployed in the rural areas around Sheberghan, under the auspices of the Ministry of National Security.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] According to photographic evidence, Dostum additionally received airborne training and still chooses to wear two first-class "Master Paratrooper" Afghan jump wings.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] As a Parcham faction member of the People's Democratic Party of Afghanistan (PDPA), he was exiled after the purge of Parcham by the party's Khalqist faction leaders, living in Peshawar, Pakistan for a while.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] After the Soviet invasion (Operation Storm-333) and installation of Babrak Karmal as head of state, Dostum returned to Afghanistan, where he started commanding a local pro-government militia in his native Jawzjan Province.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] By the mid-1980s, he commanded a force of around 20,000 paramilitaries and controlled the northern provinces of Afghanistan.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] While the unit recruited throughout Jowzjan and had a relatively broad base, many of its early troops and commanders came from Dostum's home village.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] He left the army after the purge of Parchamites, but returned after the Soviet occupation began.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] During the Soviet–Afghan War, Dostum was commanding a paramilitary battalion to fight and route mujahideen forces; he had been appointed an officer due to prior military experience.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] This eventually became a regiment and later became incorporated into the defense forces as the 53rd Infantry Division.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Dostum and his new division reported directly to President Mohammad Najibullah.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Later on, he became the commander of the military unit 374 in Jowzjan.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] He defended the Soviet-backed Afghan government against the mujahideen forces throughout the 1980s.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] While he was only a regional commander, he had largely raised his forces by himself.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] The Jowzjani militia Dostum controlled was one of the few in the country that was able to be deployed outside its own region.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] They were deployed in Kandahar in 1988 when Soviet forces were withdrawing from Afghanistan.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Due to his efforts in the army, Dostum was awarded the title "Hero of the Republic of Afghanistan" by President Najibullah.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Dostum's men would become an important force in the fall of Kabul in 1992, with Dostum deciding to defect from Najibullah and allying himself with opposition commanders Ahmad Shah Massoud and Sayed Jafar Naderi, the head of the Isma'ili community, and together they captured the capital city.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] With the help of fellow defectors Mohammad Nabi Azimi and Abdul Wakil, his forces entered Kabul by air in the afternoon of 14 April.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] He and Massoud fought in a coalition against Gulbuddin Hekmatyar.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Massoud and Dostum's forces joined to defend Kabul against Hekmatyar.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Some 4,000–5,000 of his troops, units of his Sheberghan-based 53rd Division and Balkh-based Guards Division, garrisoning Bala Hissar fort, Maranjan Hill and Khwaja Rawash Airport, where they stopped Najibullah from entering to flee.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Dostum then left Kabul for his northern stronghold Mazar-i-Sharif, where he ruled, in effect, an independent region (or 'proto-state'), often referred as the Northern Autonomous Zone.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] He printed his own Afghan currency, ran a small airline named Balkh Air, and formed relations with countries like Uzbekistan effectively creating his own proto-state with an army of up to 40,000 men, and with tanks supplied by Uzbekistan and Russia.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] While the rest of the country was in chaos, his region remained prosperous and functional, and it won him the support from people of all ethnic groups.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Many people fled to his territory to escape the violence and fundamentalism imposed by the Taliban later on.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] In 1994, Dostum allied himself with Gulbuddin Hekmatyar against the government of Burhanuddin Rabbani and Ahmad Shah Massoud, but in 1995 sided with the government again.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Following the rise of the Taliban and their capture of Kabul, Dostum aligned himself with the Northern Alliance (United Front) against the Taliban.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] The Northern Alliance was assembled in late 1996 by Dostum, Massoud and Karim Khalili against the Taliban.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] At this point, he is said to have had a force of some 50,000 men supported by both aircraft and tanks.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Much like other Northern Alliance leaders, Dostum also faced infighting within his group and was later forced to surrender his power to General Abdul Malik Pahlawan.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Malik entered into secret negotiations with the Taliban, who promised to respect his authority over much of northern Afghanistan, in exchange for the apprehension of Ismail Khan, one of their enemies.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Accordingly, on 25 May 1997, Malik arrested Khan, handed him over and let the Taliban enter Mazar-e-Sharif, giving them control over most of northern Afghanistan.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Because of this, Dostum was forced to flee to Turkey.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] However, Malik soon realized that the Taliban were not sincere with their promises as he saw his men being disarmed.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] He then rejoined the Northern Alliance and turned against his erstwhile allies, driving them from Mazar-e-Sharif.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] In October 1997, Dostum returned from exile and retook charge.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] After Dostum briefly regained control of Mazar-e-Sharif, the Taliban returned in 1998, and he again fled to Turkey.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Dostum returned to Afghanistan in May 2001 to open up a new front before the U.S.-led campaign against the Taliban joined him, along with Commander Massoud, Ismail Khan and Mohammad Mohaqiq.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] On 17 October 2001, the CIA's eight-man Team Alpha, including Johnny Micheal Spann landed in the Dar-e-Suf to link up with Dostum.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Three days later, the 12 members of Operational Detachment Alpha (ODA) 595 landed to join forces with Dostum and Team Alpha.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Dostum, the Tajik commander Atta Muhammad Nur and their American allies defeated Taliban forces and recaptured Mazar-i-Sharif on 10 November 2001.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] On 24 November 2001, 15,000 Taliban soldiers were due to surrender after the Siege of Kunduz to American and Northern Alliance forces.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Instead, 400 Al-Qaeda prisoners arrived just outside Mazar-i-Sharif.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] After they surrendered to Dostum, they were transferred to the 19th century garrison fortress, Qala-i-Jangi.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] The next day, while being questioned by CIA officers Spann and David Tyson, they used concealed weapons to revolt, triggering what became the Battle of Qala-i-Jangi against the guards.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] The uprising was finally brought under control after six days.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Dostum has been accused by Western journalists of responsibility for the suffocating or otherwise killing of Taliban prisoners in December 2001, with the number of victims estimated as 2,000.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] In 2009, Dostum denied the accusations and US President Obama ordered an investigation into the massacre, which as of August 2025, never took place.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] In the aftermath of Taliban's removal from northern Afghanistan, forces loyal to Dostum frequently clashed with Tajik forces loyal to Atta Muhammad Nur.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Atta's men kidnapped and killed a number of Dostum's men, and constantly agitated to gain control of Mazar-e-Sharif.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Through the political mediations of the Karzai administration, the International Security Assistance Force (ISA) and the United Nations, the Dostum-Atta feud gradually declined, leading to their alignment in a new political party.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Dostum served as deputy defense minister the early period of the Karzai administration.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] On 20 May 2003, Dostum narrowly escaped an assassination attempt.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] He was often residing outside Afghanistan, mainly in Turkey.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] In February 2008, he was suspended after the apparent kidnapping and torture of a political rival.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Some media reports in 2008 stated earlier that Dostum was "seeking political asylum" in Turkey while others said he was exiled.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] One Turkish media outlet said Dostum was visiting after flying there with then Turkey's Foreign Minister Ali Babacan during a meeting of the Organization for Security and Cooperation in Europe (OSCE).
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] On 16 August 2009, Dostum was asked to return from exile to Afghanistan to support President Hamid Karzai in his bid for re-election.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] He later flew by helicopter to his northern stronghold of Sheberghan, where he was greeted by thousands of his supporters in the local stadium.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Dostum was directly chosen as First Vice President of Afghanistan in the April–June 2014 Afghan presidential election, next to Ashraf Ghani as president and Sarwar Danish as second vice president.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] In July 2016, Human Rights Watch accused Abdul Rashid Dostum's National Islamic Movement of Afghanistan of killing, abusing and looting civilians in the northern Faryab Province during June.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Militia forces loyal to Dostum stated that the civilians they targeted – at least 13 killed and 32 wounded – were supporters of the Taliban.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] In November 2016, at a buzkashi match, he punched his political rival Ahmad Ischi, and then his bodyguards beat Ischi.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] In 2017, he was accused of having Ischi kidnapped in that incident and raped with a gun on camera during a five-day detention, claims that Dostum denies but that nevertheless forced him into exile in Turkey.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] On 26 July 2018, he narrowly escaped a suicide bombing by ISIL-KP as he returned to Afghanistan at Kabul airport.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Just after Dostum's convoy departed the airport, an attacker armed with a suicide vest bombed a crowd of several hundred people celebrating his return at the entrance to the airport.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] The attack killed 14 and injured 50, including civilians and armed security.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] On 30 March 2019, Dostum again escaped an expected assassination attempt while traveling from Mazar-e-Sharif to Jawzjan Province, though two of his bodyguards were killed.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] The Taliban claimed responsibility for the attack, the second in eight months.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] On 11 August 2021 during the Taliban's nationwide offensive, Dostum, along with Atta Muhammad Nur, led the government's defence of the city of Mazar-i-Sharif.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Three days later, they fled across Hairatan to Uzbekistan.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Atta Nur claimed that they were forced to flee due to a "conspiracy".
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Both men later pled allegiance to the National Resistance Front of Afghanistan, the remaining remnants of the collapsed Islamic Republic of Afghanistan.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Dostum, Atta, Yunus Qanuni, Abdul Rasul Sayyaf and some other political figures formed the *Supreme Council of National Resistance of the Islamic Republic of Afghanistan* in opposition to the new Taliban government in October 2021.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Dostum is considered to be liberal and somewhat leftist.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Being ethnic Uzbek, he has worked on the battlefield with leaders from all other major ethnic groups, Hazaras, Tajiks and Pashtuns.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] — Dostum to his aides during the rise of the Taliban in c.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] He viewed the ISAF forces attempt to crush the Taliban as ineffective and has gone on record saying in 2007 that he could mop up the Taliban "in six months" if allowed to raise a 10,000 strong army of Afghan veterans.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] As of 2007, senior Afghan government officials did not trust Dostum as they were concerned that he might be secretly rearming his forces.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Dostum is more than 183 centimetres (6.00 ft) tall and has been described as "beefy".
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] He generally prefers to wear a Soviet-style camouflage military uniform, previously having worn KLMK, having a trademark bushy moustache.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Dostum was married to a woman named Khadija.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] According to Brian Glyn Williams, Khadija had an accidental death in the 1990s which broke Dostum as he "really loved his wife".
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Dostum eventually remarried after Khadija's death.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] He named one of his sons Mustafa Kamal, after the founder of the modern Turkish Republic, Mustafa Kemal Atatürk.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Dostum has spent a considerable amount of time in Turkey, and some of his family reside there.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] Dostum is known to drink alcohol, a rarity in Afghanistan, and apparently a fan of Russian vodka.
[src:buzkashi/abdul-rashid-dostum] In 2014 when he became vice president, Dostum reportedly gave up drinking for healthy meals and morning jogs.
[src:buzkashi/acoso-y-derribo] The practice of acoso y derribo derives from the *tentaderos*, traditional tests of fighting spirit in fighting cattle, and dates from the mid-nineteenth century.
[src:buzkashi/acoso-y-derribo] The first national championship took place in Salamanca in 1970.
[src:buzkashi/acoso-y-derribo] In 2010 the Real Federación Hípica Española resolved to eliminate this competition from its official list of equestrian sports.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] The 1978 Saur Revolution, followed by the 1979 Soviet invasion, marked the first major wave of internal displacement and international migration to neighboring Iran and Pakistan; smaller numbers also went to India or to countries of the former Soviet Union.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Nearly 90% of the world’s 6.1 million Afghan refugees reside in neighboring Iran and Pakistan, with Iran hosting the largest share as of 2024.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Between 1979 and 1992, more than 20% of Afghanistan's population fled the country as refugees.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Following the Soviet withdrawal in 1989, many returned to Afghanistan, however many Afghans were again forced to flee during the civil war in the 1990s.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] A total of 6.3 million Afghan refugees were living in Pakistan and Iran in 1990.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] There were over 6 million Afghan refugees by 2000.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Most refugees returned to Afghanistan following the 2001 United States invasion and overthrow of the Taliban regime.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Between 2002 and 2012, 5.7 million refugees returned to Afghanistan, increasing the country's population by 25%.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Between 2012 and 2019, 2.4 million Afghans fled the country as refugees.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] At the time of Taliban's return to power in 2021, 2.6 million Afghans remained refugees.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Some countries that were part of the International Security Assistance Force (ISAF) established special programs to allow thousands of Afghans to resettle in the Western world.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] As stateless refugees or asylum seekers, they are protected by the well-established non-refoulement principle and the U.N.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] They receive the maximum government benefits and protections in countries such as Australia, Canada, Germany, the United Kingdom, and the United States.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] For example, those that receive green cards under 8 U.S.C. § 1159 can immediately become "non-citizen nationals of the United States" pursuant to 8 U.S.C. § 1452(b), without needing to meet the requirements of 8 U.S.C. § 1427(a).
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] This allows them to travel with distinct United States passports.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Australia provides a similar benefit to admitted refugees.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Following the Twelve-Day War, Iran began the 2025 Afghan deportation from Iran which according to sources will add up to 4 million Afghans.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] According to the International Organization for Migration (IOM), there are over five million internally displaced people in Afghanistan as of late 2021.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Military actions and violence by the warring factions usually play a major part in the displacement, although there are also reasons of major natural disasters.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] The Soviet invasion caused approximately 2 million Afghans to be internally displaced, mostly from rural areas into urban areas.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] The Afghan Civil War (1992–1996) caused a new wave of internal displacement, with many citizens moving to northern areas in order to avoid the Taliban totalitarianism.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Afghanistan has long suffered from insecurity and conflict, which has led to an increase in internal displacement.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] External influence over the past 50 years by both the Soviet Union and later the United States, along with actions of the currently ruling Taliban regime, have led to continued trends of displacement.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] The American invasion of Afghanistan (as well as the 20 years of occupation by the United States military) has contributed to the displacement of Afghan nationals.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] While many justifications were given for the invasion of Afghanistan (from revenge for the 11 September terrorist attacks, to democratization & the liberation of Afghan women), the war has led to both internal and external displacement of the Afghan population.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] On the other hand, following the 2001 invasion and otherthrow of the Taliban, millions of Afghan refugees returned to the country.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] By 2012, 5.7 million had returned, increasing the population of Afghanistan by 25%.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Native people of Afghanistan and their children lawfully reside in at least 96 countries around the world.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] About three in four Afghans have gone through internal and/or external displacement in their life.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Unlike in certain other countries, all admitted refugees and those granted asylum in the United States are statutorily eligible for permanent residency (green card) and then U.S. nationality or U.S. citizenship.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] All of their children automatically become Americans if they fulfill all of the requirements of 8 U.S.C. § 1408(4), 8 U.S.C. § 1431(a) or 8 U.S.C. § 1433(a).
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] This extends their privileges, and gives all of them additional international protection against any unlawful threat or harm.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Approximately 1,438,432 registered Afghan refugees and asylum seekers temporarily reside in Pakistan under the care and protection of the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR).
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Of these, 58.1% reside and work in Khyber Pakhtunkhwa, 22.8% in Balochistan, 11.7% in Punjab, 4.6% in Sindh, 2.4% in the capital Islamabad and 0.3% in Azad Kashmir.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Most were born and raised in Pakistan in the last four decades but are considered citizens of Afghanistan.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] They are free to return to Afghanistan under a voluntary repatriation program or move to any other country of the world and be firmly resettled there.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] The largest ever Afghan refugee camp was established in the Swabi District of Khyber Pakhtunkhwa in the north-west of the country.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Since 2002, around 4.4 million Afghan citizens have been repatriated through the UNHCR from Pakistan to Afghanistan.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Some members of the Taliban and their family have long been residing among the Afghan refugees in Pakistan.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Others such as the Special Immigrant Visa (SIV) applicants and their family members, who are awaiting to be firmly settled in the United States, are also residing in Pakistan.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] On 3 October 2023, Pakistan's Interior Minister Sarfraz Bugti ordered that all undocumented immigrants, particularly the nearly 1.73 million Afghan nationals, voluntarily leave the country by 1 November 2023 or face deportation in a crackdown.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] As of 2 April 2025, Pakistan plans to initiate arrests and deportations of Afghans living in Pakistan illegally and Afghans holding Afghan Citizen Cards on 10 April 2025.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Afghans with Proof of Registration can stay in Pakistan until 30 June 2025.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] As of October 2020, there are 780,000 registered Afghan refugees and asylum seekers temporarily residing in Iran under the care and protection of the UNHCR.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] The majority of them were born in Iran during the last four decades but are still considered citizens of Afghanistan.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] According to Iranian officials, 2 million citizens of Afghanistan who have no legal documents and over half a million Iranian visa holders also reside in various parts of the country.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Iran has long been used by Afghans to reach Turkey and then Europe where they apply for political asylum.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] As in Pakistan, the Afghan refugees are not firmly settled but reside there on a temporary basis.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Iran's initial response towards Afghan refugees, driven by religious solidarity, was an open door policy where Afghans in Iran had freedom of movement to travel or work in any city in addition to subsidies for propane, gasoline, certain food items and even health coverage.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] In the early 2000s, Iran's Bureau for Aliens and Foreign Immigrants Affairs (BAFIA) initiated registration of all foreigners, including refugees.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] It began issuing temporary residence cards to certain Afghans.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] In 2000, the Iranian government also initiated a joint repatriation program with the UNHCR.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Laws were passed in order to encourage the repatriation of Afghan refugees, such as limits on employment, areas of residence, and access to services including education.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] In 2021, the International Organization for Migration (IOM) found that just over one million Afghans have been sent back.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] In 2023, Iran along with Pakistan decided to deport more refugees.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] In May 2025, the Iranian government ordered the mass deportation of an estimated 4 million Afghan migrants and refugees.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] India hosts approximately 49,059 Afghan refugees within its borders.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] The majority of them reside in the nation's capital Delhi, specifically in the neighborhoods of Lajpat Nagar, Bhogal and Malviya Nagar.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Some of them operate "shops, restaurants and pharmacies." Afghan refugees were admitted to India during and after the Soviet–Afghan War (1979–1989).
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] A lot of the once-vibrant Sikhs in Afghanistan and Afghan Hindus have become refugees in India following the wars.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Also much of Afghanistan's Christian community thrives within India.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] In 2021, following the end of the latest war in Afghanistan, India has offered an emergency visa (the 'e-Emergency X-Misc Visa') to some citizens of Afghanistan.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Afghan refugees in India have sought asylum primarily due to political instability and conflict in Afghanistan.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] India hosts thousands of Afghan refugees, many of whom are registered with the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees (UNHCR).
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] While India is not a signatory to the 1951 Refugee Convention, it has provided long-term visas and access to education and healthcare for Afghan refugees.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] The Indian government has also pledged material support for the rehabilitation of returning Afghan refugees.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] However, challenges remain, including legal uncertainty, lack of official refugee status, and limited access to employment opportunities.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Despite these hurdles, Afghan refugees continue to integrate into Indian society, particularly in cities like Delhi, where a significant number reside.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] When the Taliban seized control of Afghanistan in August 2021, the Canadian Government announced it would resettle 40,000 vulnerable Afghans such as women and girls, members of Afghanistan's LGBTQ community, human rights workers and journalists.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] This was in addition to an earlier initiative to resettle thousands of Afghans who had worked for the Canadian Government, such as interpreters and embassy employees, as well as their families.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] By March 2022, Canada resettled 8,580 Afghan refugees.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] By August 2022, the first anniversary of the fall of Kabul, that number had risen to 17,375.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Of this $14 million, $10 million is being allocated to the United Nations High Commissioner for Refugees for essential services and recovery efforts, such as the rehabilitation of schools and health facilities, the provision of livelihood training and services associated with gender-based violence.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] The remaining $4 million will go to the World Health Organization for health services, including sexual, reproductive, maternal, neonatal, child and adolescent health care and for gender-based violence services.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] On 17 August, after the fall of Kabul, Ugandan Government announced that based on United States' request, they will be temporarily hosting 2000 Afghan refugees.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] The refugees were expected to be brought in batches of 500 to Entebbe where UNHCR has secured Imperial Hotels for their arrival and screening.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] The number of refugees currently residing in Uganda is unclear, but according to reports, Ugandan officials had confirmed the arrival of 145 refugees on Sunday, 22 August 2021.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Another 51 Afghans were received at the Entebbe International Airport by the Government of the Republic of Uganda on 25 August 2021.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Over the past 40 years, the number of Afghan immigrants living in the United States has risen from roughly 4,000 to nearly 195,000.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] The majority of this population increase has occurred between two periods: 2010-2019 and from 2021 forward.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Between the 10 year periods in the 2010s, the Afghan population rose from 54,000 in 2010 to roughly 132,000 in 2019.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Additionally, that population jumped again in 2021 in the midst of the American military withdrawal from Afghanistan, when it surged by an additional 76,000.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] On 7 August 2021, due to the threat from the Taliban, the U.S.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Although, the Department of State, on 27 April 2021, had ordered American troops to withdraw from Afghanistan by 11 September, it was not until early August 2021 that the security situation of Kabul deteriorated drastically.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] This was a time when Taliban militia were taking over Afghanistan one city and/or province at a time.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Embassy Kabul issued a security alert directing all US citizen to leave Afghanistan immediately using commercial flights if they can, and if they could not afford it, they could contact the embassy to get information regarding repatriation loan.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] On 18 August 2021, the Embassy issued another alert to US citizen and LPRs (lawful permanent residents) with their spouse and unmarried children to travel to the Hamid Karzai International Airport and enter the airport at Camp Sullivan.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] When news of this reached the ears of the many Afghan citizens trying to escape the rule of Taliban, they rushed to HKIA.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] In 2021 Afghanistan started its largest humanitarian evacuations in history, involving more than 80,000 people.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] And thus began, the second phase of Operation Allies Refuge from 15 to 31 August 2021.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Embassy once again issued security alerts advising US citizen to avoid travelling to the airport and to evacuate the Abbey Gate, East Gate and North Gate immediately.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] On 26 August 2021, CNN reported two explosions at the HKIA that killed 13 US Marines and approximately 60 Afghans outside the airport walls.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] The US admitted more than 10,000 Afghan refugees from the United Arab Emirates, which became a temporary host to them on behalf of other nations.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] However, nearly 12,000 refugees remained in the Abu Dhabi facility as of August 2022.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Refugees began to protest the slow and opaque resettlement process and the living conditions.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] The protests resurfaced in October 2022.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] A refugee who moved to Canada said they are “psychologically suffering” in the Emirati facility.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Throughout the course of Operation Allies Welcome, the United States issued humanitarian parole status to more than 76,000 evacuated Afghan nationals.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Humanitarian parole serves as a method for individuals otherwise ineligible for admission into the United States to be given temporary permission to enter the country by the Secretary of Homeland Security.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] These individuals are paroled into the country as a result of "urgent humanitarian reasons or [for] significant public benefit" In the case of Afghan nationals, this status was given for a period of 2 years, additionally granting these parolees employment authorization in the country.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Individuals granted humanitarian parole status differ from their counterparts admitted through Special Immigrant Visa (SIV) or the standard immigration process, in that they lack set pathway to achieve Lawful Permanent Residency (or Green Card) status.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] In the same month, the Department of Homeland Security (DHS) opened up a new program for Afghan nationals residing in the United States.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] The policy was put into place by the administration of President Joe Biden, and additionally allowed for the extension of employment authorization for any individual whose re-parole was approved.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Afghan parolees residing in the United States continue to face an unclear future when it comes to permanent residency.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Hundreds of former Afghan special forces who fought alongside British troops in Afghanistan have been refused resettlement to the UK.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Human rights abuses against admitted Afghan refugees and asylum seekers have been widely documented.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] They include mistreatment, persecution or torture in Pakistan, Iran, Turkey, Greece, Romania, Serbia, Hungary, Germany, the United States and several other NATO-members states.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Afghans living in Iran, for example, were deliberately restricted from attending public schools.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] As the price of citizenship for their family members, Afghan children as young as 14 were recruited to fight in Iraq and Syria for a six-month tour.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Racism, low wage jobs including below minimum wage jobs, lower than inflation rate salary increases, were commonly practiced in Europe and elsewhere.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Unsanitary conditions have been reported at US air bases, and one Afghan refugee's online post of his food portion at Fort Bliss in 2021 drew some hateful responses.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Many Afghan refugees were not permitted to visit their family members for a decade or two.
[src:buzkashi/afghan-refugees] Studies have shown abnormally high mental health issues and suicide rates among Afghan refugees and their children.
[src:buzkashi/aflx] The AFL held two official Australian Football League (AFL) pre-season AFLX competitions featuring senior AFL clubs and players, in 2018 and 2019, but these were unpopular with spectators and did not return in 2020.
[src:buzkashi/aflx] The variation continues to be promoted by the AFL Commission as a participation sport in development regions and areas, and particularly where full-sized cricket grounds are not available.
[src:buzkashi/aflx] Since the COVID-19 pandemic, AFLX has been merged with AFL 9s and retained only the X brand, co-branding AFL 9s as Junior X, Youth X and Senior X and aligning it with the more widely established 9-a-side format.
[src:buzkashi/aflx] The rules of the game differed from standard Australian rules football in some significant ways.
[src:buzkashi/aflx] The game was played on a rectangular soccer-sized pitch, allowing matches to be hosted by stadiums that usually lacked the suitable field dimensions for Australian rules football.
[src:buzkashi/aflx] AFLX was first trialled at Arden Street Oval in January 2017.
[src:buzkashi/aflx] Two months later, it was trialed at was first trialled on a soccer pitch at Lakeside Stadium in a match between the Port Melbourne Football Club and Coburg Football Club.
[src:buzkashi/aflx] AFLX pre-season competition was launched by AFL chief executive officer Gillon McLachlan at Docklands Stadium on 6 February 2018.
[src:buzkashi/aflx] McLachlan said that AFLX would help promote football internationally.
[src:buzkashi/aflx] The 2018 competition attracted more than 40,000 fans to tournaments in Adelaide, Melbourne and Sydney.
[src:buzkashi/aflx] In Melbourne, TV ratings were reported as "modest" by AFL standards, with the three events drawing an average five-city metro audience of over 120,000 on Channel Seven's secondary channels.
[src:buzkashi/aflx] The AFL made several rule tweaks midway through the second season in attempt to make it higher scoring by inflating the scoring points for behinds from 1 to 2, goals from 6 to 12 and Super Goals from 10 to 20.
[src:buzkashi/aflx] Whitten Legends Game was also played under "EJX" (modified version of AFLX named after E J Whitten) at AAMI Park in Melbourne.
[src:buzkashi/aflx] It attracted just 6,000 spectators, the lowest in the series history.
[src:buzkashi/aflx] AFLX did not return as a senior AFL competition in 2020, as AFL had a greater focus on AFLW.
[src:buzkashi/aflx] Post the COVID-19 pandemic, the AFL increased the number of players to 9, effectively merging AFLX with AFL 9s and aligning with the widely established 9-a-side format.
[src:buzkashi/aflx] The reception to the two AFL pre-season competitions among fans and the media was mostly poor, with ABC Radio Grandstand journalist Richard Hinds being particularly savage in labelling it a "hollow, unappealing, pressure-free, atmosphere-deficient, oval-in-a-rectangle hole yawn-fest".
[src:buzkashi/aflx] Con Stavros of RMIT's school of Economics, Finance and Marketing, expressed doubts about the potential of AFLX to export Australian rules football but acknowledged that using rectangular playing fields instead of the standard cricket ones would make such expansion easier.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Buzkashi began among the nomadic Asian tribes who came from farther north and east spreading westward from China and Mongolia between the 10th and 15th centuries in a centuries-long series of migrations that ended only in the 1930s.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] From Scythian times until recent decades, buzkashi has remained a legacy of that bygone era.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Games similar to buzkashi are played today by several Central Asian ethnic groups such as the Hazaras, Uzbeks, Kyrgyz, Turkmens, Kazakhs, Uyghurs, Tajiks, Wakhis and Pashtuns.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] In the West, the game is also played by Kyrgyz who migrated to Ulupamir village in the Van district of Turkey from the Pamir region.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] In western China, there is not only horse-back buzkashi, but also yak buzkashi among the Tajiks of Xinjiang.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Buzkashi is the national sport and a "passion" in Afghanistan where it is often played on Fridays and matches draw thousands of fans.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Whitney Azoy notes in his book *Buzkashi: Game and Power in Afghanistan* that "leaders are men who can seize control by means foul and fair and then fight off their rivals.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Traditionally, games could last for several days, but in its more regulated tournament version, it has a limited match time.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] During the first reign of the Taliban government in Afghanistan, buzkashi was banned as they considered the game immoral.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] After the Afghan Taliban was ousted in 2001, the sport resumed.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] When the Taliban regained power in 2021, they allowed the sport to continue.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Kazakhstan's first National Kokpar Association was registered in 2000.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] The association has been holding annual kokpar championships among adults since 2001 and youth kokpar championships since 2005.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] All 14 regions of Kazakhstan have professional kokpar teams.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] The regions with the biggest number of professional kokpar teams are Southern Kazakhstan with 32 professional teams, Jambyl region with 27 teams and Akmola region with 18 teams.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Kazakhstan's national kokpar team currently holds a title of Eurasian kokpar champions.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] A photograph documents *kokboru* players in Kyrgyzstan around 1870; however, Kyrgyzstan's kokboru rules were first officially defined and regulated in 1949.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Starting from 1958 kokboru began being held in hippodromes.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] The size of a kokboru field depends on the number of participants.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] The buzkashi season in Tajikistan generally runs from November through April.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] High temperatures often prevent matches from taking place outside of this period, though isolated games might be found in some cooler mountain areas.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] In Tajikistan and among the Tajik people of Tashkorgan in China's Xinjiang region, buzkashi games are particularly popular in relation to weddings as the games are sponsored by the father of the bride as part of the festivities.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] In Pakistan, buzkashi has traditionally been very popular in the areas bordering Afghanistan.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Although the sport is dying, it is still played by the Wakhi people of Hunza in Gilgit Baltistan and by the Pashtuns including Afghan refugees in parts of Balochistan.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Buzkashi was brought to the U.S. by a descendant of the Afghan Royal Family, the family of King Amanullah and King Zahir Shah.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] A mounted version of the game has also been played in the United States in the 1940s.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Young men in Cleveland, Ohio, played a game they called *kav kaz*.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] The men – five to a team – played on horseback with a sheepskin-covered ball.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] The Greater Cleveland area had six or seven teams.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] The game was divided into three "chukkers", somewhat like polo.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] The field was about the size of a football field and had goals at each end: large wooden frameworks standing on tripods, with holes about two feet square.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] The players carried the ball in their hands, holding it by the long-fleeced sheepskin.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] A team had to pass the ball three times before throwing it into the goal.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] If the ball fell to the ground, the player had to reach down from his horse to pick it up.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] One player recalls, "Others would try to unseat the rider as he leaned over.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] They would grab you by the shoulder to shove you off.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Mounted team-based potato races, a popular pastime in early 20th-century America, bore some resemblance to buzkashi, although on a much smaller and tamer scale.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Prior to the establishment of official rules by the Afghan Olympic Federation, the sport was mainly conducted based upon rules such as not whipping a fellow rider intentionally or deliberately knocking him off his horse.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Riders usually wear heavy clothing and head protection to protect themselves against other players' whips and boots.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] For example, riders in the former Soviet Union often wear salvaged Soviet tank helmets for protection.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] The boots usually have high heels that lock into the saddle of the horse to help the rider lean on the side of the horse while trying to pick up the goat.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Games can last for several days, and the winning team receives a prize, not necessarily money, as a reward for their win.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Top players, such as Aziz Ahmad, are often sponsored by wealthy Afghans.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] A buzkashi player is called a *chapandaz* (Pashto: چپنداز); it is mainly believed in Afghanistan that a skilful chapandaz is usually in his forties.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] People believe that a good player has undergone a long period of physical practice and observation.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Similarly, horses used in buzkashi also undergo severe training and due attention.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] A player does not necessarily own the horse.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Horses are usually owned by rich people, those wealthy enough to look after and provide training facilities for such horses.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] However, a master chapandaz can choose to select any horse and the owner of the horse usually wants his horse to be ridden by a master Chapandaz as a winning horse also brings pride to the owner.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] The game consists of two main forms: Tudabarai (lit.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] 'emerging from a mass') and Qarajai (lit.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Tudabarai is considered to be the simpler form of the game.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] In this version, the goal is simply to grab the carcass and move in any direction until clear of the other players.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] In Qarajai, players must carry the carcass around a flag or marker at one end of the field, then throw it into a scoring circle (the "Circle of Justice") at the other end.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] The riders will carry a whip to fend off opposing horses and riders.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] When the rider's hands are occupied, the whip is typically carried in the teeth.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] In summary, it is capture the flag with a goat corpse.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] The calf in a buzkashi game is normally beheaded and disembowelled and has two limbs cut off.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] It is then soaked in cold water for 24 hours before play to toughen it.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Occasionally sand is packed into the carcass to give it extra weight.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Though a goat is used when no calf is available, a calf is less likely to disintegrate during the game.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] While players may not strap the calf to their bodies or saddles, it is acceptable—and common practice—to wedge the calf under one leg in order to free up the hands.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] These rules are for matches in Kabul, otherwise they are not strictly observed.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Only five riders from each team can play in a half.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] There are two halves of 45 minutes, separated by a fifteen-minute break.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Rules of kokboru have undergone several changes throughout history.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Only four players a team are allowed to play on the field at any given time.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Teams are allowed to substitute players or their horses.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] The game is played on a field 200 meters long and 70 meters wide.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Two *kazans* – big goals with a 4.4 meters in diameter and 1.2 meters high are placed on opposite sides of a field.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] The total duration of three periods is 60 minutes.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] There is a 10-minute break between each period.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] A goal is scored each time a ulak (goat carcass) is placed in an opponent's kazan.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] A kokboru is brought to centre of the field after scoring a goal.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] It is also prohibited to ride towards the spectators or receive spectators' assistance or to start a kokboru game without giving an oath to play justly.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] In Tajikistan, buzkashi is played in a variety of ways.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] The most common iteration is a free-form game, often played in a mountain valley or other natural arena, in which each player competes individually to seize the buz and carry it to a goal.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Forming unofficial teams or alliances does occur, but is discouraged in favor of individual play.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Often, dozens of riders will compete against one another simultaneously, making the scrum to retrieve a fallen buz a chaotic affair.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Tajik buzkashi games typically consist of many short matches, with a prize being awarded to each player who successfully scores a point.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Buzkashi is portrayed in several books, both fiction and non-fiction.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] It is shown in Steve Berry's book *The Venetian Betrayal*.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Buzkashi was the subject of a book called *Horsemen of Afghanistan* by French photojournalists Roland and Sabrina Michaud.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Gino Strada wrote a book named after the sport (with the spelling Buskashì) in which he tells about his life as surgeon in Kabul in the days after the 9-11 strikes.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] O'Rourke also mentions the game in discussions about Afghanistan and Pakistan in the Foreign Policy section of *Parliament of Whores*, and Rory Stewart devotes a few sentences to it in *The Places in Between*.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Two books have been written about buzkashi which were later turned into films.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] The game is the subject of a novel by French novelist Joseph Kessel titled *Les Cavaliers* (aka *Horsemen*), which then became the basis of the film *The Horsemen* (1971).
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] The film was directed by John Frankenheimer with Omar Sharif in the lead role, and U.S. actor and accomplished horseman Jack Palance as his father, a legendary retired chapandaz.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] This film shows Afghanistan and its people the way they were before the wars that wracked the country, particularly their love for the sport of buzkashi.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] The game is also a key element in the book *Caravans* by James Michener and the film of the same name (1978) starring Anthony Quinn.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] A scene from the film featuring the king of Afghanistan watching a game included the real-life king at the time, Mohammed Zahir Shah.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] The whole sequence of the game being witnessed by the king was filmed on the Kabul Golf Course, where the national championships were played at the time the film was made.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] In Ken Follett's book, *Lie Down with Lions* (1986), the game is mentioned being played, but instead of a goat, a live Russian soldier is used.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] The game also appears in the 1988 book Rambo III by David Morrell and its film adaptation of the same year.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Based on a screenplay by Sylvester Stallone and Sheldon Lettich, the story depicts a group of horsemen playing it and inviting the main character to join them.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] In *The Kite Runner* (2003) by Khaled Hosseini, the protagonist, Amir returns to Afghanistan from the United States several years later, when the Taliban has taken over the government.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] He attends a game of Buzkashi, in which the audience was forced by the Taliban authorities circling the stadium to remain silent during the match.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] During the break, a Taliban leader, who is later revealed to be Amir's childhood enemy Assef, brings prisoners convicted of breaking the Sharia law in the stadium to be executed by stoning.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] The Taliban authorities, who were forcing the audience to be silent during the match, begin forcing everyone to cheer the stoning of the criminals.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] A number of films also reference the game.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] In *Rambo III* (1988), directed by Peter MacDonald, John Rambo (played by Sylvester Stallone) was shown in a sequence playing and scoring in a buzkashi with his mujahideen friends when suddenly they were attacked by Soviet forces.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] The Tom Selleck film *High Road to China* (1983) features a spirited game of buzkashi.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Buzkashi is described at length in Episode 2, "The Harvest of the Seasons", of the documentary *The Ascent of Man* by Jacob Bronowski.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] It is put in the context of the domestication of the horse and the effect of nomadic warbands and raiders on agricultural settlements.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] The film includes several scenes from a game in Afghanistan.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] The opening scenes of the Indian film *Khuda Gawah* (1992), which was filmed in Afghanistan and India, show actors Amitabh Bachchan and Sridevi engaged in the game.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] The game also shown in other Indian films like *Kabul Express* (2006) and *Sahasam* (2013).
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] The 2012 joint international-Afghan short film *Buzkashi Boys* depicts a fictional story centered on the game, and has won awards at several international film festivals.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] On January 10, 2013, The Academy of Motion Picture Arts and Sciences nominated *Buzkashi Boys* for an Oscar in the category of Short Film (Live Action) for the 85th Academy Awards.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Venerated Buzkashi (ulak tartysh in Kyrgyz) player, 82 year old veteran school teacher Khamid Boronov stars in 2016 feature documentary film *Letters from the Pamirs* by Janyl Jusupjan.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] Famed Buzkashi players of Jaylgan village Shamsidin and Kazyke appear in a sequence to show the elements of Buzkashi to kids from a town.
[src:buzkashi/buzkashi] A spirited Buzkashi match is one of the last episodes of the film made in Jerge-Tal Kyrgyz region in Tajikistan's north.
